Task A¶

Dataset¶

I used a churn dataset for this task - the same one as in Homework 1. It is a dataset relating characteristics of telephony account features and usage and whether or not the customer churned.

1. Select model - random forest¶

2. and 3. Select two observations and calculate variables attributions¶

I selected observations 1 and 15 as they have different target values. Decompositions of predictions for these variables can be seen below (created with both packages).

4. Observations with different variables of the highest importance¶

Observations with this property have indices 10 and 12. The highest importance variables for the first one are total_day_minutes and total_day_charge. For the second observation they are total_eve_minutes and total_eve_charge. It is worth noting that the target variable has opposite values for these observations - accordingly 1 and 0. Decompositions can be seen below.

5. Opposite attribution of a variable¶

We can once again use variables 1 and 15 for this task (their decompositions can already be found in point 2 and 3). We can see that total_day_charge and total_eve_minutes have opposite attributions for selected observations.

6. Comparison of dalex and shap packages¶

I selected 3 observations (with indices 4, 5 and 6) for this comparison. Below there are visible plots for each of them - the first plot for shap then for dalex. Decompositions produced by both packages are fairly similar. I do not see any major differences between them.

7. Models comparison - random forest and decision tree classifier¶

I selected decision tree classifier as the second model for this comparison. Below there are plotted decompositions of prediction for observation 9. This time differences are easy to spot. Variables total_day_minutes and total_day_charge have positive attributions in predictions produced by both models. However, in case of a decision tree the main variable is total_night_minutes (and its attribution is strongly negative) whereas for a random forest this feature has minor positive impact. Also total_eve_minutes is a strong negative attribute for the decision tree but is nearly irrelevant for the forest.

Task B¶

v() = 0 v(A) = 20 v(B) = 20 v(C) = 60 v(A,B) = 60 v(A,C) = 70 v(B,C) = 70 v(A,B,C) = 100

Permutation A contribution B contribution C contribution
ABC 20 60 - 20 = 40 100 - 60 = 40
ACB 20 100 - 70 = 30 70 - 20 = 50
BAC 60 - 20 = 40 20 100 - 60 = 40
BCA 70 - 20 = 50 20 100 - 70 = 30
CAB 70 - 60 = 10 100 - 70 = 30 60
CBA 100 - 70 = 30 70 - 60 = 10 60

value_A = 1 / 6 * (20 + 20 + 40 + 50 + 10 + 30) = 1 / 6 * 170 = 28.3
